[2] Brazil (Espirito Santo), horses
Date: Fri 24 Apr 2015
Source: Folha Vitoria [in Portuguese, excerpts trans. Mod.JW, edited]
http://www.folhavitoria.com.br/geral/noticia/2015/04/espirito-santo-registra-novos-casos-de-doenca-perigosa-para-cavalos.html


A disease considered rare and dangerous for horses, mules and donkeys was confirmed again in Espirito Santo [state]. Known as glanders, the disease is caused by bacteria and only in rare cases is transmitted to cats [including zoo lions and tigers -- see ProMED archive from 2011 - Mod.JW], dogs and humans. According to the Agricultural and Forest Protection Institute of Espirito Santo (IDAF), currently there are 3 outbreaks of infectious disease in the state.

IDAF confirmed an outbreak in Dr. Pedro Fontes Equine Breeding Center in Cariacica, a place that houses part of the military police squad. The other 2 glanders foci are located on private property in Viana and Guarapari. All these properties remain quarantined.

The focus is only considered closed after 2 negative results for consecutive glanders, with an interval of 45-90 days, performed in all animals of the properties. IDAF is reportedly sending guidelines that reinforce prevention and disease control methods for the agency's offices throughout the state.

On 31 Mar [2015], IDAF was notified of the occurrence of 2 possible cases of the disease in the 65 horses of the Regiment of Mounted Police in the municipality of Serra. These animals did not show any symptoms and were detected thanks to mandatory testing that is done every time the animals need to be transported within or outside the state.

In Brazil, 18 states have foci of glanders, and glanders disease incidence is notifiable to the World Organization for Animal Health (OIE), which recommends in such cases the sacrifice of the animals. This procedure was adopted in accordance with Regulations of the Ministry of Agriculture Livestock and Supply (MAPA).
