[4] Brazil: OIE reports 2014
Date: Mon 27 Apr 2015
From: Cristina Ramirez David <c.ramirezmatus@gmail.com> [edited]


The last OIE follow-up report sent by Brazil was in July 2014 (follow-up No. 8). In follow-up reports No. 7 and No. 8, no new outbreaks or cases are reported.

When one checks the WAHID Event Summary link, http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review/viewsummary?reportid=11974, the map shows only outbreaks reported in the immediate notification reports and in the follow-up reports. Based on these reports, there are 14 outbreaks, of which 2 are considered to be "continuing."

However, when one checks the semestral reports which Brazil has submitted, for the 1st semester of 2014 (which is the last available report), 57 new outbreaks were reported, yielding a total of 59 active outbreaks (57 new ones plus the 2 continuing from 2013): http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/semestrial/review?year=2014&semester=1&wild=0&country=BRA&this_country_code=BRA&detailed=1.

When a disease has become endemic in a zone, or to the entire country, that country has the option of reporting the events using the semester reports. I believe that this has been the case in this situation for Brazil. What does not "fit" is the fact that in its follow-up report for July 2014, no new cases are reported, even though there seem to be a number of new cases reported in their semester report. A final report would be helpful, indicating the current disease situation and mentioning that future information will be provided in semestral reports.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The disease, one among the oldest known and prevalent worldwide, is currently eradicated or effectively controlled in many countries. Recently, the disease appears to be re-emerging, and has been reported in Iraq, Turkey, Pakistan, India, Mongolia, China, Brazil, UAE and countries of Africa -- see ProMED archive from 2014 below.

There is a comprehensive description of glanders in: http://www.merckmanuals.com/vet/generalized_conditions/glanders/overview_of_glanders.html?qt=glanders&alt=sh#Diagnosis.

Some trivia:
- The disease was 1st described by Aristotle;
- In 1664, it was recognized as highly contagious;
- In the early 19th century, the zoonotic potential was described;
- After being eradicated in the USA in 1934, a human case was reported in 2000 in a researcher at the United States Army Medical Research Institute (USAMRIID) -- see ProMED archive from 2000 below;
- The agent was used as a biological weapon in animals during World War I in Europe and Russia. - Mod.RNA (in Portuguese, trans. Mod.JW)

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3334665,6.]
